value.name: 2MASS J11193254–1137466 AB - Wikipedia
value.snippet: 2MASS J11193254–1137466 AB is a planetary mass binary located 86±23 light-years from the Earth in the constellation Crater. The components of 2MASS J1119–1137 are each roughly four Jupiter masses. The planetary-mass objects are probably a part of the TW Hydrae association which has an age of approximately 10 million years. The planetary-mass objects are candidate rogue planets.

value.name: 2MASS J19383260+4603591 b - Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our ...
value.snippet: 2MASS J19383260+4603591 b is a gas giant exoplanet that orbits a B-type star. Its mass is 1.9 Jupiters, it takes 406 days to complete one orbit of its star, and is 0.92 AU from its star. value.name: 2MASS | IPAC
value.snippet: The Two Micron All-Sky Survey (2MASS) is a near-infrared digital imaging survey of the entire sky conducted by the University of Massachusetts and IPAC at 1.25, 1.65 and 2.17 microns. A pair of matched 1.3-m diameter telescopes (Arizona and Chile) completed survey operations in early 2001.

value.name: 2MASS J04151954−0935066 - Wikipedia
value.snippet: 2MASS J04151954−0935066 (also abbreviated to 2MASS 0415−0935) is a brown dwarf of spectral class T8, in the constellation Eridanus about 18.6 light-years from Earth. This is a reference (standard) object for the definition of the T8 spectral class.

value.name: 2MASS J05233822-1403022 Star Facts (Distance, Colour & more)
value.snippet: Based on the star's spectral type (L2.5), 2MASS J05233822-1403022's colour is brown. 2MASS J05233822-1403022 is located in the Milky Way galaxy, and this is the galaxy that you reside in. In case you're wondering, 2MASS J05233822-1403022 is not located within the Solar System, and there is only one star in the Solar System, the Sun.

value.name: Two Micron All Sky Survey – Wikipedia
value.snippet: 2MASS ist ein gemeinsames Projekt der University of Massachusetts (UMASS) und des Infrared Processing and Analysis Center (IPAC) am California Institute of Technology. Es wurde mit zwei besonders dafür eingerichteten automatisierten 1,3-m- Teleskopen durchgeführt; für den Nordhimmel am Fred-Lawrence-Whipple-Observatorium in Arizona und für den Südhimmel am Cerro Tololo Inter-American Observatory in Chile .
